PART II: ANALYSIS OF PROSPER LOAN DATA FROM 2005 TO 2014¶

BY: DAVID UGOCHUKWU ASOGWA¶

Investigation Overview¶

This data set is a loan data records from prosper Loan in the United States, it contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, interest rate, current loan status, borrower income, and many others. The report in this part would be structured to provide summary of simple univariate relationships to multivariate relationships, this research provides answers to various questions like whether the monthly loan payment has a correlation or any relationship between loan original,amount, what is the spread of lterm of loan in loan status, identifying the frequency of the categorical variables; Term of loan, borrower's employment status, year of loan, and loan status, are there differences between loans depending on how the loan term large the original loan amount was. Key insights would be generated from this to be able to make a presentation with it. In spite of the fact that the dataframe has 81 features, this study is only interested in few of the features, and after the cleaning process, only the useful columns for the purpose of this study was saved and used for analysis.

Distribution of Loan Amount¶

From the left plot, the distribution appeared to be right skewed with most loan amounts between 0 to 15,000 dollars, with a single peak value. Increasing the bin size to 40, the second plot on the left showed otherwise. The distribution peaked almost at every 50000 dollar interval: a little before 5,000, 10,000, 15,000, 20,000 and 25,000 dollars. Outlier values at 30,000 and 35,000 dollars.

Next up, monthly_payment of borrowers¶

This right plot shows a cluster of the loan payments towards the left with sharp decent in amounts being paid and high outliers towards 2,000 dollars and a single peak. The right plot shows a clearer view of the distribution which is skewed to the right with tailing in the amounts paid by the borrowers which peaked between 0 to 500 dollars.

The loan term appears to be an interesting feature¶

The loan term shows that majority of the loans taken are medium term loans with 77.14% of the loans, followed by the long and short term loans withh 21.43% and 1.43% of the total loans respectively.

Let's see what happens in the status column¶

This data explicitly shows that majority of the loans (49.29%) are still open while 33.66% are completed, which is actually a good thing. Only a few of the loans gave defaulted as seen in the past due bars. A small amount of loan have been cancelled within the period amounting to 0.004% and 0.18% of the loans are already making their final payment.

Distribution of Closed Loan Over the Years¶

It is obvious that majority of the loans are not completed with 51.289% of the total loans, year 2013 had the most number of closed loans with 10.498% of total loans closed that year and 2005 having the least with 0.007%

What is the employment_status of the borrower's?¶

Observable from the distribution, majority of the borrowers are either employed, full-time workers and self-employed. This might be a precedent that a higher percentage of loans are granted to active workers as can be seen from the retired and not-employed bars with 0.703% and 0.739% respectively, of the total loans granted.

What is the correlation between loan_amount and monthly_income?¶

From all indication, there is a strong positive correlation between the loan_amount and monthly_payment. An increase in the loan_amount gives rise to a corresponding increase in the monthly_payment.

What percentage of loans are given to borrower's whose income source are not verifiable over the years?¶

Income_verifiable feature having a True or False value is not evenly distributed over the years. It is pertinent to say that borrower's with verifiable income source have a higher possibility of getting a loan. Non verified borrower's obtained the highest loan in 2013 with only 1.971% of the total loan that year compared to 28.80% given to verified borrower's.

How is the term of the loan distributed over the list_year?¶

The medium term loans apparently have the most occurrence in all the years, with the short term loans most occurence being in 2012. The long term loan occurred most in 2013 with 11.950%. A further dive int this dataset using seaborn facetgrid will throw more light.

How is loan payment made in relation to loan amount and term of loan?¶

Having established a strong positive correlation between loan amount and monthly payment, adding an extra feature, term, to it shows another relationship. The is also a strong positive correlation between these features and aside that, it is observed that the short term loans have higher payments, followed by the medium term and long term loans. This might be as a result of the time interval needed to payup the loan amount, that is, short term loans having the time frame of 12 months requires a higher payment in order to complete it within the time frame. But long term loan with 60 months payment period will be paid in smaller bits. From the plot, it is seen also that the maximum short term loan amount is about 25,000 dollars.

Does employment_status have any effect on loan_amount and monthly_payment?¶

It appears Employed borrower's get most of the loans, as it is the most in the data points.

How does being a home_owner status affect loan_amount and monthly_payment?¶

The data points appears to be evenly distributed, though there is a slight difference as observed during univariate exploration. The home_owner status does not really contribute much, or probably have no effect on the loan being granted or not.

Loan distribution and payment over the list year.¶

Aside illustrating a strong positive correlation between loan amount and monthly payment, the above figure shows that most medium and long term loans were listed in 2013 and 2014, with a little short term loan in 2013. Other years have a sparse distribution of the long and medium term loans.
